[1] Mumps: USA (Indiana)
Date: Fri 8 Apr 2016
Source: Indy Star [edited]
http://www.indystar.com/story/news/2016/04/08/mumps-outbreak-reaches-65-mostly-colleges/82796644/


Mumps, 1st reported in February [2016] on many local college campuses, has continued to spread with a total of 65 people in Central Indiana who have now been diagnosed with the highly contagious respiratory disease, state health officials say.

While the majority of cases have occurred on college campuses, 15 community cases, unconnected to those at colleges, also have been reported, the Indiana State Department of Health said Friday [8 Apr 2016] in a news release. There have been 24 confirmed cases at Butler University, 18 at Indiana University and 4 each at Indiana University-Purdue University Indianapolis and Purdue University.

Mumps activity at the IU [Indiana University] campuses and Butler appears to be slowing, but the Purdue cases arose this week. College campuses, where many people live in close quarters with one another, are particularly rich environments in which the disease can spread rapidly.

State health officials urge college students to make sure they have been vaccinated against the disease, which can lead to puffy cheeks and a swollen jaw. Other symptoms include fever, headache and muscle aches. Some people with mumps have mild symptoms and may not even know they have the disease.

Mumps is spread up to 2 days before and 5 days after symptoms begin.

[Byline: Shari Rudavsky]

